{"type":"message","id":"090d2635","parentId":"23450ebd","timestamp":"2026-03-30T07:46:15.662Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the issue - `588000.SH` is being classified as both A股 (because it starts with \"5\" and my code checks `symbol.startswith(\"5\")` for ETF) and also as ETF (because it appears in both categories). The script's output shows:\n\n- A股 23 只\n- 港股 2 只\n- ETF 1 只 (= 588000.SH)\n\nBut the 588000.SH is counted in both A股 and ETF! It's being double-counted.\n\nLet me look at the issue more carefully:\n- My `_infer_currency_and_asset_type` function marks `588000.SH` as ETF because it starts with \"5\"\n\n\n- But the A股 filter (`currency != \"HKD\"`) still catches it since its currency is CNY\n- The ETF filter also catches it because of the \"5\" prefix\n\nSo 588000.SH gets counted in both the A股 total (23) and the ETF total (1), when it should only appear in the ETF count. The script is treating it as both an A股 and an ETF, which is the double-counting bug.\n\nLooking at the actual holdings file, 588000.SH is classified as `stock` in the CSV, but my code is overriding that to `etf` because the symbol starts with \"5\". The real problem is that `paper_portfolio_positions_latest.csv` doesn't have a proper `asset_type` column that would let me distinguish between them correctly. The distinction between 588000.SH as an index fund versus a stock symbol needs to be handled differently, maybe by checking if it's already labeled as \"fund\" in the source data rather than inferring from the symbol pattern alone.","thinkingSignature":"e6bef0943a008fc5219865e4ebc05d203fef52901a1ddce845685102e9453bbb"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_d8k9lvc51skj_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport csv\nwith open('/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/paper_portfolio_positions_latest.csv') as f:\n    rows = list(csv.DictReader(f))\nfor r in ro